==Festivals in Revolutions==

Bibliographic notice from Ross Wolfe:

"staging performances at demonstrations and political celebrations does have some revolutionary precedent.  The role of festivals in the France of the First Republic has been documented by Mona Ozouf in her book, Festivals and the French Revolution.  Likewise, the young Soviet avant-garde produced numerous plays and recreations in the 1920s designed to involve the masses in the building of a new, emancipated society.  An account of these is provided in James Von Geldern’s Bolshevik Festivals: 1917-1920."
(http://rosswolfe.wordpress.com/2011/10/12/the-theatrical-dimension-of-occupy-wall-street-a-brief-excursus-on-the-carnivalesque-in-politics/)


